00:03:51.200 --> 00:04:00.800
That's a platform of online accessibility courses. 
What is ARIA? The abbreviation means "accessible

00:04:00.800 --> 00:04:07.040
rich internet applications" - you can forget 
that right away, but what you need to know is

00:04:08.960 --> 00:04:17.520
ARIA are attributes, HTML5 attributes, 
that give extra information and feedback

00:04:17.520 --> 00:04:21.360
to assistive technology, like, 
for example, screen readers.

00:04:23.360 --> 00:04:29.440
In forms you can use it for naming form 
controls, describing extra information,

00:04:30.080 --> 00:04:37.360
and for giving feedback on dynamic changes. 
I will give you examples of that in the demos

00:04:37.360 --> 00:04:48.080
later. Before you start, you need to know: the 
first rule of ARIA is don't use ARIA. There are

00:04:48.080 --> 00:04:54.080
five rules - go and look them up when you have 
time - but the first rule is the most important.

00:04:55.040 --> 00:05:02.720
Don't use ARIA to fix meaningless and incorrect 
HTML5, use the already available elements,

00:05:02.720 --> 00:05:07.760
because then the browser and the screen reader 
knows how to operate and understand them.

00:05:08.800 --> 00:05:18.080
ARIA is about feedback not about fixing. If 
you want to join me or look up the code later,

00:05:19.200 --> 00:05:22.160
the example code is on lvl.li/aria-in-forms.

00:05:31.200 --> 00:05:34.640
These examples contain very simplified forms,

00:05:35.200 --> 00:05:41.520
and before you start nagging, no data is 
submitted; no security checks; no translation;

00:05:42.480 --> 00:05:47.120
I just want to show you what happens 
in the front end, so you get the ARIA.

00:05:51.040 --> 00:05:56.400
I will do the demos in Safari. It's 
the browser works best together with

00:05:56.400 --> 00:06:02.880
the VoiceOver screen reader. First, I'll talk 
you through how to properly name form controls,

00:06:04.160 --> 00:06:07.760
and we're going to look at the 
accessibility tree, to show how that works.

00:06:09.360 --> 00:06:13.200
And then we're going to look at two different 
forms and add descriptions and feedback.

00:06:14.960 --> 00:06:20.560
For all the people expecting me to show how to 
build new web components from scratch with ARIA,

00:06:21.200 --> 00:06:25.440
I'll share at the end of this talk, 
my opinion about going fancy in forms.

00:06:26.240 --> 00:06:28.560
Naming and describing form controls.

00:06:30.720 --> 00:06:33.840
Let's do that.

00:06:36.720 --> 00:06:45.200
Before you use ARIA, you have to have the basics 
in order. The basics - the basic HTML5 - must be

00:06:45.200 --> 00:06:54.320
correct. And then it's super important that you 
give your form control a name - an accessible

00:06:54.320 --> 00:06:58.880
name. Okay. I will show you how 
that works for a screen reader.

00:06:59.520 --> 00:07:06.480
Here we have a label, "your question," 
and a `textarea`. If you can see,

00:07:06.480 --> 00:07:15.840
you can see the label is put above the form, 
the form control - perfectly understandable.

00:07:18.560 --> 00:07:24.880
But the label is not connected to the form 
control, so a screen reader doesn't know what

00:07:24.880 --> 00:07:33.040
to announce here. You have to connect the label to 
the form control, and you can do that with a label

00:07:33.040 --> 00:07:41.280
`for` is pointing to the `id` of the form 
control. Here, the textarea has an id of

00:07:41.280 --> 00:07:52.880
`id-textarea,` so the label has a for with 
`id-textarea` - now, they are connected. I

00:07:52.880 --> 00:08:00.640
will start the screen reader and let you hear how 
important that is. Okay, let's start VoiceOver.

00:08:05.600 --> 00:08:09.360
[VoiceOver] VoiceOver on. Safari. Naming 
and describing form controls window,

00:08:09.360 --> 00:08:17.520
toolbar. [Rian] Okay. When a screen reader 
enters a form, they jump into "form mode."

00:08:18.800 --> 00:08:23.840
That gives the user the opportunity to 
type instead of operating the screen

00:08:23.840 --> 00:08:29.120
reader. and then you can jump with tab key 
from focusable element to focusable element.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:34.480
So, I'll tab now in the first form 
control. [VoiceOver] Leaving toolbar.

00:08:34.480 --> 00:08:38.880
Entering Naming and Describing form 
controls web content. Edit text, blank.

00:08:38.880 --> 00:08:44.080
[Rian] About the form field

00:08:44.080 --> 00:08:47.720
textarea, it announces "edit text, blank."

00:08:51.360 --> 00:08:59.040
So, it is an edit text field. "Blank" is "I have 
no name." If I tab to the next one, that has

00:08:59.040 --> 00:09:04.400
a `for` and `id` connection: [VoiceOver] 
your question edit text. [Rian] Then it

00:09:04.400 --> 00:09:10.720
says "your question, edit text." And then a 
screen reader user knows what to fill out.

00:09:11.520 --> 00:09:16.960
So without a connection [VoiceOver] "edit text. 
blank." With a connection? [VoiceOver] "Your

00:09:16.960 --> 00:09:26.400
question, edit text." [Rian] Okay. That must 
be in order. Uh, you have to have a name for

00:09:26.400 --> 00:09:35.840
the form control. You can use a placeholder - is a 
placeholder replacement for a label? No, it isn't,

00:09:37.520 --> 00:09:44.320
but screen readers get smarter and smarter. In 
this case, I have a textarea with a placeholder,

00:09:44.320 --> 00:09:50.160
"your question." Let's listen how that sounds. 
[VoiceOver] "Your question, edit text, blank."

00:09:53.360 --> 00:09:59.040
"Your question." [Rian] So the screen reader 
announces "your question," the placeholder,

00:09:59.760 --> 00:10:04.480
and then tries to figure out what's the 
name. Cannot come up with the name, so it

00:10:04.480 --> 00:10:06.800
guesses, okay, the placeholder must be the name.

00:10:08.560 --> 00:10:13.600
Not all screen readers do this, so 
don't depend on this always working.

00:10:16.560 --> 00:10:22.000
There's also another issue with this. 
The placeholder text disappears when

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:26.080
you start typing, or when the field 
is filled out with an autocomplete.

00:10:27.680 --> 00:10:33.520
People may forget what to fill out, or need 
to check if the right value is added to the

00:10:33.520 --> 00:10:40.400
right fields with an autocomplete. Always 
add a visual label to prevent errors.

00:10:45.040 --> 00:10:53.600
So the next thing you can do with ARIA, is give 
a form control a name with an `aria-label.` In

00:10:53.600 --> 00:11:00.480
this case, textarea, aria-label "your question." 
If I tab into this: [VoiceOver] Your question,

00:11:00.480 --> 00:11:06.320
edit text. [Rian] It's announced perfectly 
well, but there's no visual label.

00:11:10.080 --> 00:11:15.600
You can have a placeholder and an aria-label: 
[VoiceOver] Your question, edit text, describe

00:11:15.600 --> 00:11:21.760
your question. [Rian] The placeholder is announced 
in a different voice, "describe your question"

00:11:22.560 --> 00:11:28.640
and aria-label is "your question," 
but still you have no visual label.

00:11:31.840 --> 00:11:34.240
You can use an `aria-labelledby.`

00:11:36.400 --> 00:11:43.280
Instead of the element `label,` you can 
use, for example, a `div` - yay, a div.

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:52.400
But you have to connect both together, and 
that you do with `aria-labelledby.` You give

00:11:52.960 --> 00:12:03.440
the div an `id` and in the form control textarea 
you say labeled by referring to that id.

00:12:05.760 --> 00:12:12.320
How is that announced? [VoiceOver] Your question, 
edit text. [Rian] Perfectly okay. I have no idea

00:12:12.320 --> 00:12:19.920
why you should use a div instead of a label, but 
maybe you have some obscure use case for this.

00:12:23.680 --> 00:12:33.280
Next one. `aria-describedby,` and this is super 
useful. As I told you, you jump into form mode

00:12:36.400 --> 00:12:47.280
and then, you only get announced what is connected 
to the form control. So in this case, if you have

00:12:47.280 --> 00:12:54.960
your new password, and you have an input for your 
password, and below that, the rules "please use a

00:12:54.960 --> 00:13:01.360
password of minimal eight characters," that also 
must be connected to the input field. Otherwise,

00:13:01.360 --> 00:13:07.040
the screen reader doesn't announce it, because 
the screen reader doesn't know it's connected.

00:13:08.560 --> 00:13:11.040
And that you do with aria-describedby.

00:13:13.440 --> 00:13:17.120
The paragraph with extra 
information, you give that an

00:13:17.120 --> 00:13:25.120
id, and in the input field, the form control, 
you say aria-describedby referring to that id.

00:13:26.360 --> 00:13:30.000
[VoiceOver] Your new password, 
secure edit text with autofill menu.

00:13:32.960 --> 00:13:36.040
Please use a password of 
minimal 8 characters. [Rian]

00:13:36.560 --> 00:13:42.560
You notice there is a time lapse between 
announcing the label and announcing

00:13:43.920 --> 00:13:48.600
the aria-describedby information, 
that's a safari issues. [Unintelligible]

00:13:52.080 --> 00:13:58.560
...which will solve it, soon but now you 
first hear the label and then you hear the

00:13:58.560 --> 00:14:06.400
added paragraph so you get all the information you 
need with a form control. Next topic: icons. How

00:14:06.400 --> 00:14:12.640
do you announce an icon? Which of course the 
screen reader cannot know what's in an icon.

00:14:14.720 --> 00:14:21.440
Well, in this form you have a label with a 
search, an input field, and a button. And the

00:14:21.440 --> 00:14:30.640
button has a class that this font also classes, 
displays an icon of a search and loop. If you

00:14:30.640 --> 00:14:37.920
can see this it's perfectly okay, but how does 
this announce? [VoiceOver] Search, edit text.

00:14:39.080 --> 00:14:47.520
[Rian] If I give the button focus I hear 
nothing. So I have to give the button a name.

00:14:51.280 --> 00:14:57.920
And that you can do with aria-label. 
`aria-label="Submit search."` you put

00:14:57.920 --> 00:15:04.400
that on the button all the content inside 
the button is omitted, only the aria-label

00:15:04.400 --> 00:15:12.800
is announced. Now, let's see what it does. 
[VoiceOver] Search, edit text. [Rian] I still

00:15:12.800 --> 00:15:20.480
hear nothing - that's weird! I put an aria-label 
on it. I will mute the screen reader now.

00:15:23.360 --> 00:15:25.840
And now, I'm going to inspect the code.

00:15:28.640 --> 00:15:36.080
And then, I see button class 
`font-awesome`, aria-label

00:15:36.080 --> 00:15:41.600
"submit search" and then font awesome 
added "aria-hidden"=true to it.

00:15:43.600 --> 00:15:50.640
That's because font awesome thinks, "Okay, if 
it's an icon, better hide it from screen readers,

00:15:50.640 --> 00:15:57.360
because they cannot pronounce it." 
But if you put a font awesome icon

00:15:57.360 --> 00:16:01.200
directly on a focusable element, on 
an element that really makes sense,

00:16:03.360 --> 00:16:05.600
and you put an aria-hidden through that,

00:16:05.600 --> 00:16:10.320
the screen reader doesn't know what it is. 
It omits it, think, "Okay, it doesn't exist."

00:16:12.560 --> 00:16:14.000
What's the workaround for that?

00:16:18.640 --> 00:16:26.400
You move the class of the font awesome class out 
of the button. Of, actually, you move it inside

00:16:26.400 --> 00:16:35.840
the button, in a `span` and you give the class 
to a span. So the button has the aria-label only,

00:16:35.840 --> 00:16:42.720
and the span with the font awesome class with 
the loop icon is inside, and it's in the span.

00:16:44.880 --> 00:16:50.800
That way the label aria-label is 
announced. Now, let's see what...

00:16:52.960 --> 00:17:00.640
I'll close this. So let's move from the 
start. [VoiceOver] Search, edit text.

00:17:02.040 --> 00:17:09.760
[Rian] You hear nothing. [VoiceOver] Search, edit 
text. [Rian] Scroll up a bit, you hear nothing,

00:17:10.320 --> 00:17:14.320
and then, with the span inside the 
button: [VoiceOver] Search, edit text,

00:17:14.960 --> 00:17:21.600
submit search button. [Rian] Then the button is 
announced. Okay. Keep this in mind: not every,

00:17:21.600 --> 00:17:26.960
this aria-hidden is generated by font 
awesome so, don't put it on an element

00:17:26.960 --> 00:17:31.840
that needs to be announced, that needs to 
have a label, because it will be hidden.

00:17:36.400 --> 00:17:43.920
You can actually check what the accessible name is 
